2026-04-21 01:35:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control-module input cable pair between power-supply module and control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The measurement shows the power-supply module itself is producing the correct polarity and magnitude (about −12 V wrt ground on its + lead and 0 V on its − lead) and there is no inversion between its two output cables.\n\nHowever, the control-module red LED (inverted‑cables indicator) is lit and the main lamp is off. That LED is designed to light when the line coming from the power supply that *should* be at 0 V is actually at +12 V with respect to the other line. Since the PSU output polarity is correct, the only way for the indicator LED to see an inverted condition is if the two cables from the PSU are cross‑connected at the control module—i.e., the cable intended to be the +12 V line is plugged into the control module’s 0 V input terminal, and the cable intended as 0 V is plugged into the control module’s +12 V input terminal.\n\nThis is a configuration fault in the cable pair between the power-supply and control modules: the two connectors are swapped at the control-module side (or, equivalently, the PSU + cable is mated with the control-module 0 V input and vice versa). Correcting this misconnection should extinguish the control-module red LED and allow the downstream diode and lamps in the load module to be properly forward biased when the switch is closed, restoring normal lamp operation.'
