2026-04-21 01:35:55 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power-supply module internal wiring between battery jack and PSU Output Cable (+)', 'battery input jack positive terminal connection'] hypothesis_explanation='The measurements show PSU Output (−) at 0 V and PSU Output (+) sitting at about −12 V relative to ground, with no inversion between the two output cables themselves. Visual inspection then revealed that the battery jack negative terminal is correctly wired to PSU Output (−), but the jack positive terminal has no direct connection to either output cable. Instead, PSU Output (+) is only connected through the internal resistor (used for the green LED indicator) at its port ‘p’. This leaves the output ‘+’ floating except via the LED/resistor path, so the module cannot deliver a proper +12 V rail and the green power LED never lights. Because the control-module polarity relative to the supply is effectively reversed, the red “inverted cables” LED comes on even though the external cabling is nominal. Repairing the positive-side wiring from the battery jack so that the jack’s positive terminal directly feeds PSU Output Cable (+) (while keeping the LED/resistor in parallel) will restore correct +12 V, turn on the green LED, extinguish the red LED under normal wiring, and allow the load lamp to work when the switch is closed.'
