Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: control-module cable connections and red-LED orientation,
DESCRIPTION: With the system powered as currently wired, use a multimeter to measure the voltage across the control-module’s red LED (indicator) and its series resistor: place probes on the two internal nodes of the LED–resistor series string. Record polarity (which side is more positive) and magnitude when the red LED is ON. Then trace/verify which external cable (from the PSU) each side of this LED–resistor string ultimately connects to, to determine whether the indicator circuit is wired opposite to the design (i.e., turning on when polarity is actually correct rather than inverted).,
RESULT: The red LED anode is at −0.0021 V and its cathode at −1.2938 V, giving about 1.29 V across the LED with the anode more positive when ON. The series resistor has about 10.69 V across it (−11.9872 V on the PSU (+) side, −1.2938 V on the LED side). POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED: the LED side of the series string connects to PSU Output Cable (−), and the resistor side connects to PSU Output Cable (+).
