2026-04-21 01:36:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control-module inverted-cable indicator LED orientation / wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the PSU outputs are correctly referenced (PSU − ≈ 0 V to true ground, PSU + ≈ −12 V) and that there is no polarity inversion between PSU and control-module cabling. However, across the control-module’s red LED+resistor string we see about 12 V with current flowing from PSU Output Cable (+) (at ≈ −12 V) through the resistor into the LED and then to PSU Output Cable (−) at ≈ 0 V, with the LED anode more positive than its cathode by about 1.29 V. Tracing confirms that the resistor side of the string is tied to PSU (+) and the LED side to PSU (−), i.e. the indicator is wired opposite to the original design description: it lights when polarity is actually correct rather than inverted. Because the red LED is ON while the green PSU LED is OFF and the main lamp is OFF, the only consistent fault is that the inverted-cables indicator circuit (LED orientation and/or its connections to the two control-module input lines) is reversed relative to the intended behavior. Repair consists of correcting the orientation/connection of this LED indicator circuit so it is reverse-biased for correct polarity and forward-biased only when the input cables are swapped.'
