2026-04-21 01:36:39 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['polarity of the external 12 V source plug with respect to its markings / intended convention'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal module wirings and components (PSU output cables, jack wiring, control-module indicator circuit, load-module diode and lamps) test as correctly connected and functional. Yet the measured system reference shows PSU Output Cable (−) at 0 V and PSU Output Cable (+) at about −12 V with respect to a true battery-positive reference. Inside the control module, the red LED is forward biased between PSU (+) and PSU (−) exactly as per its design for an inverted supply condition, and it is lit. In the load module, the series diode is oriented so that it would conduct only if PSU (+) were truly more positive than PSU (−); with PSU (+) actually at −12 V, that diode is reverse biased, so both lamps sit near 0 V and remain off. The power‑supply green LED is wired to light only when the jack’s ‘positive’ terminal is actually positive; since the external source delivers opposite polarity relative to the jack’s assumed convention, that LED never forward biases and stays off. All of this is consistent with one single root cause: the external 12 V source’s plug is wired with its polarity reversed relative to the markings/assumptions of the system (e.g., center pin negative instead of positive on a barrel plug, or battery leads reversed in the case/connector). Repair should consist of correcting the plug wiring or using a correctly polarized 12 V source so that the jack’s “pos” terminal becomes +12 V and “neg” is 0 V.'
