2026-04-21 01:36:49 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power-supply module internal reference / labeling of PSU Output Cable (+) vs (−) used by downstream modules'] hypothesis_explanation='All component-level tests (source, jack wiring, control-module LED path, load-module diode and lamps) are nominal. Measurements consistently show that the conductor the documentation calls “PSU Output Cable (+)” sits at about −12 V with respect to the true source positive, while “PSU Output Cable (−)” is at 0 V. The control-module inverted-polarity LED is wired exactly as designed *with respect to these labels*: it lights when its ‘+’ input (PSU Output Cable (+)) is negative relative to its ‘−’ input (PSU Output Cable (−)), which is what we now have. The load-module diode is also correctly oriented with respect to the intended polarity, so it remains reverse-biased and blocks current to both lamps when the labeled rails are reversed. The green LED on the PSU, which is wired directly across the actual source terminals, is OFF only because the rest of the system is referencing the wrong conductor as +12 V; it is not a failed LED but a reference mismatch.\n\nThus the root cause is not a failed discrete component but that the entire downstream system (control and load modules) is referencing the PSU cables with swapped logical roles: the wire labeled/assumed as ‘+’ within the overall design is in fact the negative rail, and vice versa. Correcting the assignment (or re-terminating the two PSU output leads so the physically +12 V conductor is treated as the system + rail and the 0 V conductor as the system − rail) will restore proper operation of the green LED, extinguish the red inverted-cable indicator under normal polarity, and allow the load-module diode to conduct so the lamp turns on when the switch is closed.'
